  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Develops global standards for preventing money laundering\n- Recommends legal and regulatory measures\n- Identifies high-risk jurisdictions\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Sets standards for banking regulations\n- Provides guidance on preventing financial crimes\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Standards\n- Monitors and assists countries in developing anti-money laundering frameworks\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish consistent regulations across EU member states\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Helps track potential money laundering activities\n\n7. Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\nThese frameworks require countries to criminalize money laundering, implement reporting requirements, and cooperate in international investigations.\n\nIndividual countries also have their own specific anti-money laundering laws and regulations that align with these international standards.",
